{
  "answer": "In Urdu ghazals, the *maqta* is the final couplet (or *sher*), in which the poet incorporates their *takhallus* (pen name) as a signature. This allows for a personal, often witty or poignant capstone to the poem's themes of love, longing, or existential reflection.\n\n**Ghalib's style**, as seen in his ghazal \"Aa ke meri jaan ko qarar nahin hai\" (Diwan-E-Ghalib, Ghazal 1), favors direct address (\"O Ghalib\") integrated into a wry, self-deprecating observation. The maqta reads:\n\n> You've sworn an oath, O Ghalib, to give up the wine,[^1]  \n> But in your vow, the faith of any prayer is not there.[^1]\n\nHere, Ghalib mocks his own hypocrisy—vowing sobriety like a pious prayer, yet admitting its insincerity—turning the signature into a philosophical punchline that undercuts spiritual pretense with human frailty.[^1]\n\n**Zauq's style**, by contrast, employs an exclamatory lament (\"Ah Zauq\") in his ghazal \"Ae Zauq waqt naale ke rakh le jigar pe haath\" (Diwan-E-Zauq, Ghazal 5), embedding the name amid raw emotional surrender. The maqta reads:\n\n> Ah Zauq, I fell, and clutched my heart, its every door ajar,[^2]  \n> when she just stood, with such a grace, and on her hip she laid a hand.[^2]\n\nZauq's self-naming evokes urgent pathos, portraying the poet as overwhelmed by the beloved's casual allure, with the takhallus heightening the drama of capitulation rather than irony.[^2]\n\nGhalib's maqtas thus lean toward intellectual detachment and paradox, using the signature to provoke reflection, while Zauq's are more viscerally immersive, leveraging it for heightened sentiment.\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/01-aa-ke-meri-jaan-ko-qarar-nahin-hai/translation/#p-4304e1).\n\n[^2]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/05-ae-zauq-waqt-naale-ke-rakh-le-jigar-pe-haath/translation/#p-938be9).",
